<br>
Marshall just realized that because he could convict or acquit, he essentially had the power of judicial review if he chose to use it.<br>
<br>
A jury can do exactly the same thing.<br>
<br>
There is not greater or lesser support for one or the other in the Constitution.<br>
<br>
The bottom line is that juries DO have that power.  Perhaps they weren't designed to, but a jury CAN acquit on those grounds, and if they do so, the acquittal is binding.  Thus, they DO have the power of judicial review.<br>
<br>
