<br>
The Constitution specifices that the Legislative Branch makes the laws, the Executive Branch enforces the laws, and the Judicial Branch determines if the law has been broken.<br>
<br>
The only power a jury has, by design, is to determine whether the law has been broken.<br>
<br>
Juries are instructed to follow the law and to weigh the evidence on the merits of the case.  If the jury does not act in accordance with the law then the judge is bound to override the verdict and call a mistrial. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2171<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/3/03 2:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=137>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Freedom of Religion</span><hr size=1> The judge cannot override a verdict of innocent, only a guilty verdict.<br>
<br>
The Constitution does not explicitly grant the power of judicial review to the judicial branch.  Essentially, as designed, the courts are just there to determine if a law has been broken (like you said actually).  The power of judicial review is however implicit in the powers granted to the courts by the Constitution.<br>
<br>
The bottom line is that a jury can acquit on any grounds they want to.  The acquittal is binding.  Thus, they have the power of judicial review.  Whether they should or were intended to are other issues.  They probably weren't.  I don't believe that the courts were actually intended by the founding fathers to have the power of judicial review, yet they exercise it.<br>
<br>
The legislative branch could pass a law stating that the courts do not have the power of judicial review.  It would be a meaningless law and would have no power.  The judge can tell the jury they cannot practice judicial review, but if the court finds someone innocent, they are innocent (no double jeopardy).<br>
<br>
Both of these powers are unintended, but they necessarily are contained within the powers explicitly granted.<br>
<br>
Note the way you yourself phrased it:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>the Judicial Branch determines if the law has been broken<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The only power a jury has, by design, is to determine whether the law has been broken.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Both these institutions are designed to determine if a law has been broken.  You essentially described their explicit powers are being similiar in nature.<br>
<br>
You can make a strong argument that juries shouldn't be doing it since they don't really have the understanding of the law to do it.  Also, it would create chaos and laws would not be uniformly enforced.  Whether or not it's good, juries do possess the power.<br>
<br>
